Public Health Discovery Portal                                                               Skip to Navigation | Skip to Content                                                                                         go                                                       New York University              New York University                Global Public Health Discovery Portal                                 Public Health In Action                     Knowledge Development                     Professional Development                     Conversations                Resources                           Resources Home | Data sources | Reference, Research & Advocacy Materials | Topics, Programs, and Projects                                      Text Size        Print        Email        PUBLIC HEALTH RESOURCES              Quick Navigation      Epidemiology and biostatistics      Environmental and occupational health      Health, development, and poverty      Health promotion and communication      Health services, systems, and management      Immigrant and refugee health      Infectious diseases      Linking education and health      Maternal and child health      Mental health      Non-communicable diseases and injury      Nutrition and hunger      Oral health      Policy and politics      Resources Home             The pages in this section offer links to organizations broadly recognized for the quality of their work on specifc public health issues. Those with a more general focus are listed on the Reference, Research and Advocacy Materials page.     PUBLIC HEALTH TOPICS, PROGRAMS AND PROJECTS           Health, development, and poverty     Eldis, a knowledge arm of the Institute of Development Studies (IDS) at the University of Sussex, describes its aim as sharing the best in development policy, practice and research. Its extensive reference library includes not just resources on economics, trade and finance but pieces specifically on HIV and AIDS, health, health and fragile states, health systems and human resources for health. Some references are in “dossier” format, which include context, case studies and recommended readings. The IDS site holds additional resources: including research summaries, working papers, discussion papers, research reports, practice papers, in focus policy briefings, and development bibliographies, most of which are downloadable free of charge.     The Center for Global Development is “an independent, nonprofit policy research organization that is dedicated to reducing global poverty and inequality and to making globalization work for the poor,” and its site has hundreds of working papers, briefs, books, essays, and more. It also offers several of their own datasets, including on HIV prevalence and treatment and on African health workers abroad.     Publications offered by The Microcredit Summit Campaign are on the themes of reaching the poorest, reaching and empowering women, building financially self-sufficient institutions and ensuring a positive, measurable impact on the lives of clients and their families. Projects include integrating microfinance and health education and the Financing Healthier Lives: Microfinance and Health Integration Advocacy Booklet.     Princeton University ’s Center for Health and Wellbeing (CHW) is to foster “research and teaching on the multiple aspects of health and wellbeing” and “to understand the determinants of health and wellbeing and the role that public policy plays in shaping the quality of people’s lives.” As such, it offers long lists of working papers, descriptions and findings from their research programs and projects, and research briefs. Public Health Discovery Portal                                                               Skip to Navigation | Skip to Content                                                                                         go                                                       New York University              New York University                Global Public Health Discovery Portal                                 Public Health In Action                     Knowledge Development                     Professional Development                     Conversations                Resources                           Resources Home | Data sources | Reference, Research & Advocacy Materials | Topics, Programs, and Projects                                      Text Size        Print        Email        PUBLIC HEALTH RESOURCES              Quick Navigation      Epidemiology and biostatistics      Environmental and occupational health      Health, development, and poverty      Health promotion and communication      Health services, systems, and management      Immigrant and refugee health      Infectious diseases      Linking education and health      Maternal and child health      Mental health      Non-communicable diseases and injury      Nutrition and hunger      Oral health      Policy and politics      Resources Home             The pages in this section offer links to organizations broadly recognized for the quality of their work on specifc public health issues. Those with a more general focus are listed on the Reference, Research and Advocacy Materials page.     PUBLIC HEALTH TOPICS, PROGRAMS AND PROJECTS           Health, development, and poverty     Eldis, a knowledge arm of the Institute of Development Studies (IDS) at the University of Sussex, describes its aim as sharing the best in development policy, practice and research. Its extensive reference library includes not just resources on economics, trade and finance but pieces specifically on HIV and AIDS, health, health and fragile states, health systems and human resources for health. Some references are in “dossier” format, which include context, case studies and recommended readings. The IDS site holds additional resources: including research summaries, working papers, discussion papers, research reports, practice papers, in focus policy briefings, and development bibliographies, most of which are downloadable free of charge.     The Center for Global Development is “an independent, nonprofit policy research organization that is dedicated to reducing global poverty and inequality and to making globalization work for the poor,” and its site has hundreds of working papers, briefs, books, essays, and more. It also offers several of their own datasets, including on HIV prevalence and treatment and on African health workers abroad.     Publications offered by The Microcredit Summit Campaign are on the themes of reaching the poorest, reaching and empowering women, building financially self-sufficient institutions and ensuring a positive, measurable impact on the lives of clients and their families. Projects include integrating microfinance and health education and the Financing Healthier Lives: Microfinance and Health Integration Advocacy Booklet.     Princeton University ’s Center for Health and Wellbeing (CHW) is to foster “research and teaching on the multiple aspects of health and wellbeing” and “to understand the determinants of health and wellbeing and the role that public policy plays in shaping the quality of people’s lives.” As such, it offers long lists of working papers, descriptions and findings from their research programs and projects, and research briefs. Public Health Discovery Portal                                                               Skip to Navigation | Skip to Content                                                                                         go                                                       New York University              New York University                Global Public Health Discovery Portal                                 Public Health In Action                     Knowledge Development                     Professional Development                     Conversations                Resources                           Resources Home | Data sources | Reference, Research & Advocacy Materials | Topics, Programs, and Projects                                      Text Size        Print        Email        PUBLIC HEALTH RESOURCES              Quick Navigation      Epidemiology and biostatistics      Environmental and occupational health      Health, development, and poverty      Health promotion and communication      Health services, systems, and management      Immigrant and refugee health      Infectious diseases      Linking education and health      Maternal and child health      Mental health      Non-communicable diseases and injury      Nutrition and hunger      Oral health      Policy and politics      Resources Home             The pages in this section offer links to organizations broadly recognized for the quality of their work on specifc public health issues. Those with a more general focus are listed on the Reference, Research and Advocacy Materials page.     PUBLIC HEALTH TOPICS, PROGRAMS AND PROJECTS           Health, development, and poverty     Eldis, a knowledge arm of the Institute of Development Studies (IDS) at the University of Sussex, describes its aim as sharing the best in development policy, practice and research. Its extensive reference library includes not just resources on economics, trade and finance but pieces specifically on HIV and AIDS, health, health and fragile states, health systems and human resources for health. Some references are in “dossier” format, which include context, case studies and recommended readings. The IDS site holds additional resources: including research summaries, working papers, discussion papers, research reports, practice papers, in focus policy briefings, and development bibliographies, most of which are downloadable free of charge.     The Center for Global Development is “an independent, nonprofit policy research organization that is dedicated to reducing global poverty and inequality and to making globalization work for the poor,” and its site has hundreds of working papers, briefs, books, essays, and more. It also offers several of their own datasets, including on HIV prevalence and treatment and on African health workers abroad.     Publications offered by The Microcredit Summit Campaign are on the themes of reaching the poorest, reaching and empowering women, building financially self-sufficient institutions and ensuring a positive, measurable impact on the lives of clients and their families. Projects include integrating microfinance and health education and the Financing Healthier Lives: Microfinance and Health Integration Advocacy Booklet.     Princeton University ’s Center for Health and Wellbeing (CHW) is to foster “research and teaching on the multiple aspects of health and wellbeing” and “to understand the determinants of health and wellbeing and the role that public policy plays in shaping the quality of people’s lives.” As such, it offers long lists of working papers, descriptions and findings from their research programs and projects, and research briefs. Public Health Discovery Portal                                                               Skip to Navigation | Skip to Content                                                                                         go                                                       New York University              New York University                Global Public Health Discovery Portal                                 Public Health In Action                     Knowledge Development                     Professional Development                     Conversations                Resources                           Resources Home | Data sources | Reference, Research & Advocacy Materials | Topics, Programs, and Projects                                      Text Size        Print        Email        PUBLIC HEALTH RESOURCES              Quick Navigation      Epidemiology and biostatistics      Environmental and occupational health      Health, development, and poverty      Health promotion and communication      Health services, systems, and management      Immigrant and refugee health      Infectious diseases      Linking education and health      Maternal and child health      Mental health      Non-communicable diseases and injury      Nutrition and hunger      Oral health      Policy and politics      Resources Home             The pages in this section offer links to organizations broadly recognized for the quality of their work on specifc public health issues. Those with a more general focus are listed on the Reference, Research and Advocacy Materials page.     PUBLIC HEALTH TOPICS, PROGRAMS AND PROJECTS           Health, development, and poverty     Eldis, a knowledge arm of the Institute of Development Studies (IDS) at the University of Sussex, describes its aim as sharing the best in development policy, practice and research. Its extensive reference library includes not just resources on economics, trade and finance but pieces specifically on HIV and AIDS, health, health and fragile states, health systems and human resources for health. Some references are in “dossier” format, which include context, case studies and recommended readings. The IDS site holds additional resources: including research summaries, working papers, discussion papers, research reports, practice papers, in focus policy briefings, and development bibliographies, most of which are downloadable free of charge.     The Center for Global Development is “an independent, nonprofit policy research organization that is dedicated to reducing global poverty and inequality and to making globalization work for the poor,” and its site has hundreds of working papers, briefs, books, essays, and more. It also offers several of their own datasets, including on HIV prevalence and treatment and on African health workers abroad.     Publications offered by The Microcredit Summit Campaign are on the themes of reaching the poorest, reaching and empowering women, building financially self-sufficient institutions and ensuring a positive, measurable impact on the lives of clients and their families. Projects include integrating microfinance and health education and the Financing Healthier Lives: Microfinance and Health Integration Advocacy Booklet.     Princeton University ’s Center for Health and Wellbeing (CHW) is to foster “research and teaching on the multiple aspects of health and wellbeing” and “to understand the determinants of health and wellbeing and the role that public policy plays in shaping the quality of people’s lives.” As such, it offers long lists of working papers, descriptions and findings from their research programs and projects, and research briefs.
